</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8E15063B8EA240941939BC9338AA39B8" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="diagnostic description">
<paragraph id="5C5B22B040E48AF87E23E27D9942625F" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Diagnostic description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0970A892BA63D9A86F344DC69C0E1034" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B96C358CF57CFBAA3D3C641A51244C81" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Mandible lacinia mobilis a stemmed distally expanded, irregularly cusped blade</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="95E106AE40DB2C2D369A17FFE6C69863" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Maxilla 1</emphasis>
inner plate with pappose setae lining inner margin; 
<emphasis id="F2A0420FD3183337806EA051495FDFF9" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">palp 1-articulate</emphasis>
. Maxilla 2 inner plate broader than outer, inner and outer plates subequal in length. Maxilliped palp article 4 vestigial. 
<emphasis id="050408FA9F22D9F76C7BB530FC63D9D8" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Gnathopod 1 coxa reduced</emphasis>
, slightly shorter than coxa 2, margins slightly tapering distally; basis swollen, without glandular material; dactylus reduced, simple. Pereopod 3 carpus short to long, longer than wide. 
<emphasis id="D4369D4F222BA94EA7527B9A6EF85901" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Pereopod 4 with well-developed, subacute posteroventral lobe</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A517EBC47A356268BA998402C981E4CA" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="08C37C29325B0286477CA3ACF3791F7A" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E0DF1FECD87A6C500D95FB9F5B342196" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
The name is a combination of the prefix 
<emphasis id="212BB66B9DEE02474AED3362DB71F510" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Austro</emphasis>
- from the latin 
<emphasis id="D1FF05D6FB5D973041D6C8F1F4DDC8D8" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">australis</emphasis>
, meaning southern and referring to the southern hemisphere distribution of the type species, and the suffix - 
<emphasis id="DBABF6BF8DE61A96B9BC5A8F73E04A85" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">callisoma</emphasis>
(gender neuter) referring to its placement within the 
<taxonomicName id="6EE977842A1F50C02039FA5A8567D116" authorityName="Kilgallen &amp; Lowry" authorityYear="2015" family="Scopelocheiridae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Paracallisominae">Paracallisominae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3D3E56E8FEBC6BD92383BED41CDFDF01" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="FDC152C4CDAA9D50011C0A5FACE85C7A" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B1C3956B05FF75A9BF967D9343790546" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicName id="A6CC69ABC3B5063E23704B1052F460F9" authorityName="Kilgallen &amp; Lowry" authorityYear="2015" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Austrocallisoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Austrocallisoma" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="29D6E6E43AD50846A90F1D96E6BECC3D" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Austrocallisoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
gen. n. is a difficult taxon that has much in common with the monotypic genera 
<taxonomicName id="66589FF494E3359E3DE192E9D3B283CC" authorityName="Hendrycks &amp; Conlan" authorityYear="2003" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Anisocallisoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anisocallisoma" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9236A8626C068964AEE5008E3361DF90" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Anisocallisoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="35ABC2CAD2DF60D464FDC6CB3B6C7C1D" authorityName="J. L. Barnard" authorityYear="1961" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Eucallisoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eucallisoma" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="ACDD1DA1C72562AA674A11D21716083B" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Eucallisoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="9A0BB7F576CC1667B540EA788CB2364B" authorityName="Kilgallen &amp; Lowry" authorityYear="2015" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Tayabasa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tayabasa" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="35F04FCBEB89D7DC6FEA3BF6615A86D7" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Tayabasa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
gen. n. Having four monotypic genera that are highly derived yet clearly closely related is not ideal. However, to maintain consistency of diagnostic characters at a generic level we feel justified in establishing this new genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A07B02FBAB0F409CB4B8080792AC21B4" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicName id="1E1C0846669160BF504C00E0302024C3" authorityName="Kilgallen &amp; Lowry" authorityYear="2015" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Austrocallisoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Austrocallisoma" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="828FA963C96F674DD3E52F37B5FA64FE" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Austrocallisoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be separated from both 
<taxonomicName id="6C6D1A37748C2E1F80201C527B0F43EA" authorityName="J. L. Barnard" authorityYear="1961" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Eucallisoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eucallisoma" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EA4168C7922FB202B076894EEF170E4C" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Eucallisoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="7C3EE93BA948AF53400C6DF10D457BA5" authorityName="Hendrycks &amp; Conlan" authorityYear="2003" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Anisocallisoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anisocallisoma" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="68958633B83CC70CA97A48014950E864" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Anisocallisoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the strongly developed and subacute posteroventral lobe on the pereopod 4 coxa (well-developed and subquadrate in 
<taxonomicName id="53DD179BD69BA02774412BB484F5FFD9" authorityName="J. L. Barnard" authorityYear="1961" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Eucallisoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eucallisoma" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="663CCBDF876E47D646A9973B6702D688" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Eucallisoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, very weakly-developed and subacute in 
<taxonomicName id="BC621DC876613390FFD435EE46684921" authorityName="Hendrycks &amp; Conlan" authorityYear="2003" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Anisocallisoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anisocallisoma" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="10D4008D68C301EB2385B52492098C4F" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Anisocallisoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). It can be further distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="F0BEC169051F7D5607F942EBB0C62D2B" authorityName="Hendrycks &amp; Conlan" authorityYear="2003" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Anisocallisoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anisocallisoma" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="640AF930147DA1FD654D0130C2664A66" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Anisocallisoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having plumose setae lining the inner margin of the inner plate of maxilla 1, and having a distal tuft of setae on the accessory flagellum. It differs from 
<taxonomicName id="C5443621C49F582A4E377CFECDD4D7CB" authorityName="J. L. Barnard" authorityYear="1961" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Eucallisoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eucallisoma" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B31B21CE12486B582F97DD8598D0CD5D" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Eucallisoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a vestigial maxilliped palp article 4 (well-developed in 
<taxonomicName id="1DA19EF29DCE1BCC2FB50ABC937BD43C" authorityName="J. L. Barnard" authorityYear="1961" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Eucallisoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eucallisoma" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="09DBBCC7C1EFA994FB1DA6ACDB33E434" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Eucallisoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
